Comment 1: 
A pressing question is why we would price Asian options with deep learning in the first place.
The most common pricing method currently for Asian options (that use arithmetic averages) is 
with monte carlo simulations. The issue with this approach is that many iterations are needed,
and the parameter space needs to be updated repeatedly. Once a deep learning model is trained,
it only needs the current parameter values and will return a predicted value quickly, only 
having to reference its own price distribution.   


Comment 2: 
We need a reasonable range for our parameters. As we read more of the literature we will 
hone in on fair ranges, but for now we will take Claude's word on the following: 

Spot Price S - Fixed at 100 (Not necessary to vary it, we care about the relationship between S and K)
Strike Price K - [70,130] (Covering deep ITM, ATM, and deep OTM)
Risk-Free Rate r - [0.01,0.10]
Volatility sigma - [0.05,0.60]
Time to Maturity T - [0.1,2.0] (Years)
Number of Dates to Average n - 12 (monthly), 52 (weekly), and 252 (daily).


Comment 3: 
Now we need to address how we will generate our data. Two viable methods are with uniform sampling
from each parameter range, and Latin hypercube sampling (LHS). LHS is just going to ensure that we more
thoroughly fill the space, as with six dimensions it is not clear how many samples it will take for 
the uniform approach to do the same. There is also the problem of clustered data which uniform sampling 
is prone to.

We will also start by generating 100k sample options, but may increase this number in future iterations.
Due to the relative niceness and simplicity of the problem, we may not need the huge amount of data that 
deep learning is known for.

